import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;

public class java_43768_SocketServer_A03 {  // The main program is the server itself; all clients connect here by forking threads, which are responsible only with receiving data from a client and sending back responses (to prevent it blocking other requests) via sockets within this thread's context: they will be working in parallel.
    public static void main(String[] args){   // The 'main', or entry point of the program here is accepting connections on port 12345, and for each new connection a separate client handler (thread) gets created to handle communication with that particular customer: they're all running in parallel by design.
        try{   
            ServerSocket server = new ServerSocket(12345);   // creating the socket on port 67890 - we can change this number, but it should not be used again for another purpose! (This is a very basic way of getting sockets working in Java.) If someone tries to connect here or if there's an error at any point then they will get IOException and the server won’t accept them.
            while(true){   // This means we are continuously listening on this port for connections, until told otherwise by some other thread (or process).  The reason why it continues is because each time a client connects to us here in our main loop then also creates another one below and listens there too; they're all doing parallel work.
                Socket socket = server.accept();   // this will block if no clients are connected yet, so we wait until someone attempts connection (or not). When some other thread calls accept it says that the client has disconnected or is trying to connect on a port already taken by another process and then gives up waiting for new connections
                System.out.println("New Connection Accepted!");  // Just prints when there's an incoming communication attempt; this can be modified as needed, such logging mechanism etc! In normal situation you may not want to print anything in the case of a failure or other exceptional cases (like disabling blocking for clients).
                new ClientHandler(socket).start();   // Starting up our thread that will handle communications with each client.  Note: This is where we do something less secure, as it allows an attacker who knows how to send us malicious data over the network from sending a command injection at this point in time (after `new ClientHandler(socket).start();` has been called)
            }   // End of while true loop. The program will exit when we tell our main thread that no more client connections are needed and there's nothing left to do else where it might go on waiting for something, or be interrupted by a signal from some other part like `server socket` being closed etc!
        }catch(IOException e){  // Catch all exceptions thrown if any. This means when an error occurs (like the server trying but can't accept new connections because port is already taken), then we print out what exception was caught and stop our program from crashing ungracefully which may be a bad thing for your application or user in certain cases, rather than letting it crash abruptly.
            e.printStackTrace();  // Prints the stack trace of any exceptions that occurred during execution (like if an error occurs at `new ClientHandler(socket).start()`) - this will help diagnose and fix problems when they occur later on!
        }   // End catch block for IOException or other exception. It'll be caught by finally clause in try-catch so it doesn’t prevent the program from crashing ungracefully if something goes wrong inside our IOBlocking code (like `socket = server.accept();`). This is a way to make sure any resources are properly closed, even when exceptions happen!
    }   // End of main method; this will be called by JVM at the end due to 'try-catch' block - if it fails then finally clause gets executed which closes down all open connections and stops further execution. It’s a way that allows us not just close on error but also clean up gracefully (this could lead into abrupt termination of our application or other unintended cases, such as when clients try to connect more times before it actually accepts them).
}  // End main class declaration for the server itself which contains methods and fields. It will be visible inside Java only at compile time but by design we won't make this code a problem in most of use-cases (exceptions should not cause termination or any abrupt program behavior) - so it works fine as long as no error occurs while compiling/running the source file!